english:
  title: Memorial Stele for Lord Fang, Grand Commandant of the Imperial Household and Prime Minister of the Upper Luo Estate
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fifth year of Zhizheng, on the day yiwei of the fifth month, the Left Deputy Commandant of the Imperial Secretariat, Minister Inbok, conveyed the royal decree to the Institute of Literary Talent and History, saying: "The late Prime Minister and Lord of the Upper Luo Estate, Minister You, served in the great empire and received abundant favor and trust. Through his devotion, he strengthened our kingdom. Though he has now passed beyond the veil, his memory dwells in my heart. Therefore, I command the director of this institute to inscribe the record of his deeds upon stone, that future generations might draw inspiration."

    I humbly examine the records: The Fang family has for generations been among the gentry of Oseng County in Gyeongsang Province. His great-grandfather Youxian was posthumously honored as Marquis of Henan. His grandfather Liang was elevated to Duke of the Henan Commandery. His father Deshe served as Grand Commandant and Duke of the Loyalty State. His mother, Lady Kim, was honored as Grand Lady of the Loyalty State. His wife, Lady Lee, daughter of the Intimate Counselor Guangshi, was enfeoffed as Lady of the Loyalty State—all receiving these honors through the Prime Minister's elevation.

    The Prime Minister's childhood name was Little Duke. During King충렬's reign, he served in the palace, taking the name Minister You. The Grand Princess of Qi possessed a nature at once severe and luminous, sparing not even a hair's breadth from her reproof; yet through careful diligence alone, he daily earned her confidence. In the twenty-sixth year of Zhiyuan, accompanying the Princess to the court, he was presented to the Eastern Palace. The Empress Yusheng beheld him once and commanded him to remain, bestowing upon him the name Menggu'tai. When Emperor Chengzong honored the Empress Yusheng as Empress Dowager, he specially appointed Menggu'tai Grand Commandant of Offerings and Keeper of Audience Protocols, soon raising him to Grand Master of Abundant Offerings and Director of the Palace Treasury.

    During the reign of Emperor Wuzong, serving the Empress Dowager Shouyuan at Xingsheng Palace, his post was changed to Director of the Bureau of Public Works, promoted to Grand Commandant of Regular Offerings and concurrently Keeper of Protocols. The Emperor declared: "Menggu'tai has labored faithfully in palace administration and is advanced in years. I commend his service." The Empress Dowager replied: "From the days of my predecessor to this hour, I have seen him grow ever more diligent, never once wavering." He was advanced to Grand Commandant of Excellent Salary and Prime Minister, retaining his other posts. The Emperor further remarked: "The Koryo people excel at formal script—who can undertake the journey to commission a sutras written in gold? None but Menggu'tai suffices." When the sacred work arrived in the capital laden upon its cart, the Empress Dowager observed: "I knew well that Menggu'tai possesses both agility and reverence; such a one may be entrusted with great affairs."

    The Empress Dowager Taidingas treated him with increasing favor. When certain aging eunuchs of the imperial seraglio slandered him, she declared: "Menggu'tai, schooled since the days of Empress Yusheng, has mastered the laws and ceremonies—you cannot match his standing." She especially appointed him Grand Preceptor of the Crown Prince, later transferring him to Director of the Bureau of Imperial Ceremonies. In the second year of Tianli under Emperor Wenzong, he was elevated to Grand Commandant of Excellent Salary and Director of the Bureau of Auspicious Celebrations. Serving seven emperors and one empress dowager, overseeing secret deliberations and offering counsel—all met with imperial approval. Repeatedly he received gifts of sable robes, pearls, vestments, caps, gold, jade, and seven-jeweled belts, as well as four thousand acres of fertile fields in Jiangnan and treasuries of gold, silver, and imperial notes beyond reckoning.

    In the third year, he petitioned to retire eastward to his homeland. He restored the Temple of Zen Awakening to magnificent splendor, daily walking its grounds to witness the blessings of his rank and honor. Occasionally summoning kinfolk and old friends, he spent a decade or more in leisured ease, playing chess and zithers. When our present Emperor called him back to court in the summer of Zhizheng, he was seventy-six years old yet remained vigorous, causing the sovereign to marvel. He was rewarded with dragon-embroidered robes and ten thousand notes in imperial currency. The following year in the ninth month, he fell to a minor ailment and died at his residence on a gengyin day, receiving from the throne honorific gifts of silver for his interment, and being sent home with full ceremony for burial. His tomb stands on the hill behind the temple where a memorial shrine was erected in his honor. Thus from first to last he received glory and favor—truly without regret.

    As for his loyalty to our kingdom: during the Zhidai years of Emperor Wuzong, when Hong Zhongxi, Right Counselor of Liaoyangprovince, denounced King Chungseon and sought legal confrontation at court, Prime Minister Fang entered the Xingsheng Palace to attend the Empress Dowager. Seeing troubled expression upon his countenance, she inquired the cause. Kneeling, he replied: "Hong Zhongxi is a fugitive subject of Koryo, and now seeks to bring the King before the court as defendant. Moreover, the King's nature is upright and strong; he cannot bear such humiliation. I fear I shall not see my lord again—this weighs upon my heart." Tears fell upon his robes. The Empress Dowager was moved to understanding, reported the matter to the Emperor, and immediately Hong Zhongxi was banished.

    Early in the Huangqing era, when the Barbarian King Eight-Donkey-Migrant-Thought brought his people to seek allegiance, the court deliberated settling them east of the Yalu. Prime Minister Fang advised: "Koryo's land is narrow and mountainous, lacking fertile grounds for cultivation or pasture. Northern peoples would never flourish there, only causing disorder among our people." Emperor Renzong accepted this wisdom and abandoned the plan.

    When Luoshou, the Jurchen Yelü Xiyì, was appointed official of the Zhendong Province with commission already in hand, Prime Minister Fang reported to Xingsheng Palace: "Koryo's service to the imperial house spans many generations. Their dress, ceremonies, and rites remain unchanged by imperial grace alone. To dispatch Luoshou and the others—would this not contradict the intention of our founding Emperor?" Upon this, imperial decree came forth staying their mission.

    When Daolacha served as Left Prime Minister, he vigorously advocated establishing a provincial administration in Koryo. Prime Minister Fang advised the Central Palace to remonstrate with the ministers in similar terms, and Daolacha's proposal was abandoned. Through these actions, both Kings Chungseon and Chungstuk honored him with proper courtesy. He was enfeoffed as Lord of Upper Luo, ranked as Three-Times Grand Peer, and given the title Eminent Servant of Devoted Loyalty and Supporting Brilliance. The present sovereign has further commanded his virtues inscribed in stone for eternal radiance. Such honors and commendations know no end.

    Consider: our kingdom has received successive favors from the imperial court through marriage alliances; many palace retainers have found connection at the celestial gates. Yet those who preserve their trust and rank through loyalty and faith are rare indeed. How much rarer one who, guiding imperial virtue, brings benefit to his native land? Such a one as Prime Minister Fang merits our admiration. Thus I compose this inscription:

    *In the courts of heaven,*
    *Four stars gleam bright—*
    *The sovereign's trusted companions.*

    *Illustrious Lord Fang,*
    *Selected from the Eastern seas,*
    *Entered the inner halls to serve.*

    *Swift and luminous his mind,*
    *Reverent and true his heart,*
    *Proclaiming virtue through his deeds.*

    *His spirit, ever eastward turned,*
    *Held his homeland close,*
    *Guarding the kingdom he loved.*

    *In the sacred hall his portrait shines,*
    *No fault mars the record,*
    *All rests complete and perfect.*

    *This polished stone bears witness,*
    *Inscribed with verses of praise,*
    *For posterity to honor and emulate.*
  footnotes:
    - Menggu'tai (忙古台) is the Mongol name bestowed upon Minister You by Empress Yusheng. The Chinese text alternates between his Korean and Mongol names, reflecting his dual service in both cultures.
    - The Four Stars reference refers to the four most prominent stars in the Celestial Palace constellation, traditionally symbolizing imperial favor and proximity to power.
    - The poem appended to the inscription (the 'Ming') consists of six couplets, each marked with a celestial reference (基一, 基二, etc.), an elevated literary convention of the era.
